<span class="displaytext">arlington, va -- u.s. senator (candidate full)'s presidential campaign today released its latest television ad entitled "troops." the ad highlights (candidate full)'s record of not calling a single oversight hearing on nato's mission in afghanistan, not visiting in iraq for over 900 days, not supporting our troops when he voted against critical funding in 2007 and not visiting our wounded troops in germany when he made time to go to the gym but cancelled trips to ramstein and landstuhl. the ad will air in key states. <p><b>view the ad here: <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=49hc9tpp_ry">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=49hc9tpp_ry</a></b> </p><p><b><u>script for "troops" (tv :30)</u></b> </p><p><i><b>anncr: </b>(candidate full) never held a single senate hearing on afghanistan.</i> </p><p><i>he hadn't been to iraq in years.</i> </p><p><i>he voted against funding our troops.</i> </p><p><i>and now, he made time to go to the gym, but cancelled a visit with wounded troops.</i> </p><p><i>seems the pentagon wouldn't allow him to bring cameras.</i> </p><p><i>(candidate full) is always there for our troops.</i> </p><p><i>(candidate last). country first.</i> </p><p><i><b>(candidate full):</b> i'm (candidate full) and i approve this message.</i> </p><p><b><u>ad facts: script for "troops" (tv :30)</u></b> </p><p><i><b>anncr:</b> (candidate full) never held a single senate hearing on afghanistan.</i> </p><p><b>(candidate full):</b> "i became chairman of this committee at the beginning of this campaign, at the beginning of 2007. so it is true that we haven't had oversight hearings on afghanistan." (msnbc (PARTY NAME) presidential debate, 2/26/08) </p><p><i><b>anncr:</b> he hadn't been to iraq in years.</i> </p><p>the new york times: (candidate full) had not been to iraq for over 900 days. "for months, senator (candidate full) and other (PARTY NAME)s have been criticizing senator (candidate full) for not having visited iraq in a long time, even running a daily tally that is now well past 900 days." (larry rohter, "a mixed take by (candidate last) camp on (candidate last)'s trip to war zones," the new york times, 7/19/08) </p><p align="left"><i><b>anncr:</b> he voted against funding our troops.</i> </p><p>(candidate full) voted against providing $94.4 billion in critical funding for the troops in iraq and afghanistan. (h.r. 2206, cq vote #181: passed 80-14: r 42-3; d 37-10; i 1-1, 5/24/07, (candidate last) voted nay) </p><p><i><b>anncr:</b> and now, he made time to go to the gym, but cancelled a visit with wounded troops. seems the pentagon wouldn't allow him to bring cameras.</i> </p><p><b>(candidate full) cancelled a planned visit to ramstein and landstuhl in germany. </b>"spiegel online has learned that (candidate last) has cancelled a planned short visit to the rammstein and landstuhl us military bases in the southwest german state of rhineland-palatinate. the visits were planned for friday. (candidate full) will not be coming to us,' a spokesperson for the us military hospital in landstuhl announced. i don't know why.' shortly before the same spokeswoman had announced a planned visit by (candidate last)." (der spiegel website, http://www.spiegel.de, accessed 7/24/08) </p><p><b>(candidate last) senior strategist david axelrod said the pentagon told the campaign that (candidate full) "should not come."</b> "though the rammstein visit had been planned for days, (candidate last) senior strategist david axelrod said that that pentagon notified an (candidate last) military advisor only yesterday or the day before that he should not come. the pentagon 'viewed this as a campaign event and therefore they said he should not come,' axelrod said. (candidate last) has been at the base in previous overseas trips. he visited with troops--even played basketball--when he touched down in kuwait during the iraq and afghanistan leg of his swing." (lynn sweet, "pentagon tells (candidate last) not to visit u.s. troops at german base because it would be too political," chicago sun times' "sweet" blog, http://blogs.suntimes.com, posted 7/25/08) </p><p><b>"the [military] official said 'we didn't know why' th e request to visit the wounded troops was withdrawn. '</b>he ((candidate last)) was more than welcome. we were all ready for him." (jim miklaszewski and courtney kube, "what's not on (candidate last)'s schedule..." msnbc's "first read," http://firstread.msnbc.msn.com, posted 7/24/08) </p><p><b>military "prepared to accommodate (candidate last)'s traveling press and campaign staff at the passenger terminal at ramstein air base."</b> "morrell said the u.s. military was prepared to accommodate (candidate last)'s traveling press and campaign staff at the passenger terminal at ramstein air base, the u.s. air force base in southern germany where (candidate last)'s plane had been cleared to land." (michael finnegan and peter spiegel, "(candidate last)'s cancellation of a military hospital visit leaves unanswered questions," los angeles times' "top of the ticket" blog, 7/25/08) </p><p><b>defense department press secretary geoff morrell: </b>"sen. (candidate last) is more than welcome to visit landstuhl or any other military hospital around the world. ... but he has to do so, just as any other senator has to do so, in his official capacity. it is not acceptable to do so as a candidate." (michael finnegan and peter spiegel, "(candidate last)'s cancellation of a military hospital visit leaves unanswered questions," los angeles times' "top of the ticket" blog, 7/25/08) </p><p><b>defense department:</b> "but the pentagon certainly did not tell the senator that he could not visit landstuhl." "pentagon spokesman bryan whitman told reporters later friday the pentagon did not explicitly say (candidate last) should not visit the base, but was concerned with whether his capacity there would be one of a presidential candidate, not a senator. 'we do have certain policy guidelines for political campaigns and elections. and what is appropriate and what is not appropriate in those situations. but the pentagon certainly did not tell the senator that he could not visit landstuhl,' whitman said." (alexander mooney and sasha johnson, "pentagon was concerned with (candidate last) visit to hospital," cnn's "political ticker" blog, 7/25/08) </p><p><b>(candidate last) campaign explanation "didn't square with the defense department explanation."</b> "on (candidate last)'s flight from berlin to paris, gibbs offered more details. around july 15, the pentagon approved (candidate last)'s visit. but military officials later invoked a rule on political activity at military bases and questioned whether it would cover (candidate last)'s visit, gibbs said. (candidate last) spokesmen said they were seeking clarification on what the rule is. gibbs also declined to speculate on why the pentagon did not cite the rule until wednesday. that account, however, didn't square with the defense department's explanation. the pentagon said it informed the (candidate last) campaign on monday that he and his senate staff could visit landstuhl, where wounded soldiers from iraq and afghanistan are treated, but that no press would be allowed." (michael finnegan and peter spiegel, "(candidate last)'s cancellation of a military hospital visit leaves unanswered questions," los angeles times ' "top of the ticket" blog, 7/25/08) </p><p><b>the pentagon reportedly informed (candidate last) that he and his senate staff were permitted to visit landstuhl, but "no press would be allowed" in military base.</b> "the pentagon said it informed the (candidate last) campaign on monday that he and his senate staff could visit landstuhl, where wounded soldiers from iraq and afghanistan are treated, but that no press would be allowed." (michael finnegan and peter spiegel, "(candidate last)'s cancellation of a military hospital visit leaves unanswered questions," los angeles times' "top of the ticket" blog, 7/25/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) "would not have been able to address the media or make any campaign-related statements."</b> "a memo sent out wednesday from undersecretary of defense david chu explained that (candidate last)'s visit to such a military facility would be limited under these circumstances. (candidate last) would not have been able to bring any of his campaign staff -- only one senate staffer and security. he also would not have been able to address the media or make any campaign-related statements." ("(candidate last) camp: visit to troops would have seemed too political," fox news, 7/25/08) </p><p><b>before his thursday speech, (candidate full) went to the ritz carlton to work out while in berlin.</b> "still, (candidate last), just like george w. bush in the 2000 election, managed to squeeze in his workout time despite a heavy schedule of high-level meetings with government officials and his big speech at the siegessule, or victory column, around 7 p.m. berlin time. '4:49 p.m.: (candidate last) enters the luxury ritz carlton hotel wearing a t-shirt, black sweatpants and white trainers -- apparently to work out in the hotel's gym. he kept up the campaigning on the way there, smiling and waving at tourists and other onlookers,' the breathless spiegel ticker reported." (jill zuckman, "(candidate full) gets a workout at ritz gym," chicago tribune's "swamp" blog, http://www.swamppolitics.com , posted 7/24/08) </p><p><b>after his thursday speech, (candidate full) joined his campaign staff and the press corps for a martini at a berlin restaurant.</b> "after the speech was over, the candidate, in a celebratory mood, joined his campaign staff -- and the press corps traveling with him -- for dinner and a very dry vodka martini with olives at a downtown berlin restaurant." (karen tumulty, "(candidate last) urges unity in berlin," time, www.time.com, 7/24/08) </p><p><b>(candidate full) said that he was going to have some "down time" in berlin and that he "would love to tour a little bit."</b> "(candidate last) noted that in a break from his whirlwind schedule, 'we've got some down time tonight. what are you guys gonna do in berlin? huh? huh? you guys got any big. plans? i've never been to berlin, so...i would love to tour around a little bit.'" (jake tapper, "(candidate last) on tonight's berlin speech: "a crapshoot"," abc news' "political punch" blog, http://blogs.abcnews.com, posted 7/24/08) </p><p><i><b>(candidate full):</b> i'm (candidate full) and i approve this message.</i></p></span>



